{"type":"message","id":"9c608023","parentId":"1cb7de25","timestamp":"2026-05-03T04:09:49.167Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The xurl output includes ANSI color codes and error messages mixed with the JSON. Let me try a different approach - maybe I can use the browser to look at a specific tweet with a video, or just update the pipeline to handle videos differently.\n\nActually, let me step back. The xurl API response for likes doesn't include media. But the actual tweet objects do. I could look at specific tweets that I know have videos based on the text (e.g. \"embedded video\" or \"pic.x.com\" or \"video\" in the URL).\n\nLet me check what I already know from the tweet text - posts with \"https://t.co/...\" URLs that are video links. But actually, the better approach is to just set up the system correctly and test it with a known video tweet.\n\n\nSo my strategy is to save the transcription pipeline for when I have the proper video URLs, but I can at least build out the framework to handle the media field once it's accessible. Looking at the X API v2 docs, media requires expansions parameter to return those fields. The collected likes don't have media data because it wasn't included in the initial fetch, so I'll note this limitation and move forward with what I can do now.\n\nI'm thinking I should close the browser and summarize what I've found with the video transcription setup, then explain the next steps for integrating video support once we can access the media field properly.\n","thinkingSignature":"d8214a29d40b29ed52d7d2fe41b760bfe75c9850fd2aa1ad318c792597176b60"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_mjdrmz5a6li7_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"xurl \"/2/tweets/2050011880886784235?tweet.fields=entities,created_at&expansions=entities.media.media_keys&media.fields=type,url,variant_duration_ms\" 2>&1 | grep -v '^\\[' | grep -v '^\\[31m' | head -80","timeout":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minim