{"type":"message","id":"eb4bc056","parentId":"e61349f3","timestamp":"2026-05-03T04:13:10.160Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The browser can see the likes page. The videos show a \"Play Video\" button. This confirms Option A will work. \n\nNow I need to think about the practical approach here. Scraping 1,176 posts through the browser one by one would take literally forever. What I really need is to find the tweets with videos and process those specifically.\n\nFrom the snapshot, I can see some tweets have videos - like the first one (davidfigueira's post about $52k/month offers) and Simone Canc's post. These have \"Play Video\" buttons.\n\nWhat I should do:\n1. Scroll through the page to load content and find video posts\n\n\n2. For each one, grab the tweet ID and video URL, download the video, transcribe it, then save the summary before cleaning up. But this approach would be incredibly time-consuming and tedious with 1,176 posts to sift through.\n\nLet me think about a smarter way to approach this.\n\nI should write a script that uses the browser to automatically scroll through the likes page, identify which posts contain videos, and then batch process those. Then I can set up a cron job to do this every 24 hours. The issue is that when you scroll on X, new tweets load dynamically, and I'd need to track pagination to know where I left off. A full scroll through 1,176 posts would take over an hour minimum, and I still need to handle the actual downloading and transcription. Let me reconsider the strategy here.\n\nFor the initial comprehensive pass, I should focus on collecting video posts more efficiently instead of manually scrolling through everything. Then going forward, I'll check the most recent likes daily to catch new ones with videos.\n\nI think the best approach is to write an automation script that uses the browser to scroll through and find video tweets, downloads and transcribes them, then saves everything. After the initial scan, I can set up daily cron jobs to check for new likes. I should also clarify with Bobby how often he wants this to run and whether I should use the browser automation or find a more efficient method for the ongoing checks.\n\nThe browser approach is working well for individual post analysis, so I'll keep that as the backbone of the system. Now I need to think about building out the daily workflow - checking for new liked posts since the last scan, processing any videos, and then presenting the findings.\n\nFor ongoing monitoring, I'm realizing the checkpoint approach is simpler than trying to paginate through all likes. I'll store the most recent like ID from each run, then on the next scheduled check, fetch new likes from that point forward and process any new video content. This way I can just focus on the transcription and analysis work during each session. the most recent `created_at` timestamp to establish a cutoff point. I can see from the JSON data that the most recent like was from `2026-05-02T00:49:00.000Z`, so I can use that as the marker for where the daily check should start from.\n\nFor the ongoing 24-hour cycle, I'll fetch new likes in reverse chronological order, grab only tweets created after my last checkpoint, process any video content, and update the checkpoint when done. Now I need to explain this to Bobby and also address his second question about whether I'm going to run these daily scans as a cron job.","thinkingSignature":"b2cd04e9d754f95ba3e8ffbf40ff10ad5d83a926390fc9c8ac70d129a4239333"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nGood news — browser approach works. I can see the likes page with your 1,176 posts, and videos show the \"Play Video\" button. The automation will work.\n\nHere's what I'll do now:\n\n1. **Initial scan:** Scroll through your likes page, collect all tweets with videos, download + transcribe them\n2. **Set up daily cron:** Every 24hrs, check for NEW likes since last run, process any new video posts\n3. **Save checkpoint:** Last tweet ID processed, so I always know where I left off\n\nThis means:\n- First run processes everything (1,176 posts, find videos within them)\n- Each daily run after that only checks what's NEW since yesterday\n- If no new videos, I tell you \"No new video likes since last check\"\n\n**One question:** Should the 24hr check run automatically (I just handle it silently), or do you want me to announce it here first? You said you wanted to clarify before I start looking through — but for ongoing daily checks, should I just run automatically and report findings, or always check with you first?\n\nAlso — should this 24hr scan include your **bookmarks** too, or just likes? Or just likes for now?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":2774,"output":932,"cacheRead":89600,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":93306,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1777781569396,"responseId":"0645fe41f602308139e8eb33ea4dd013"}}
